  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation against money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US) first introduced reporting requirements\n- Initial focus on drug-related financial crimes\n\n2. International Collaboration:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed global standards for combating money laundering\n- Created 40 recommendations for international cooperation\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- 1990s: Enhanced reporting requirements\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) expanded anti-money laundering provisions\n- Increased financial institution compliance obligations\n- Stricter customer identification procedures\n\n4. Recent Developments:\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Expanded beneficial ownership disclosure requirements\n- Increased cross-border information sharing\n\n5. Technological Adaptations:\n- Advanced AI and machine learning detection systems\n- Real-time transaction monitoring\n- Blockchain tracing capabilities\n\n6. Global Regulatory Trends:\n- Stricter penalties\n- More comprehensive risk assessment frameworks\n- Greater transparency requirements\n- Increased international regulatory coordination\n\nThe legislation continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and complex laundering techniques.",
